Side channel attacks exploit indirect information like power use, timing, or sound to secretly gather data from a device, bypassing normal security. Instead of breaking encryption directly, attackers watch how a device behaves during operations to find clues about secret keys or passwords. Protecting against this means hiding these clues or using special hardware. Searching terms like “timing attacks,” “power analysis,” or “hardware side channels” can provide more insight. Knowing about these hidden risks helps improve security and keeps sensitive data safer in private communications.